01:28.708 --> 01:31.086
I was asking Till, I said you know,

01:31.087 --> 01:35.793
what's with all, you know, the fire
and everything about the fire

01:35.958 --> 01:37.631
where does this come from?

01:38.167 --> 01:40.545
And he looks at me and says:

01:40.958 --> 01:43.677
There are three kinds of fire!

01:43.833 --> 01:49.044
First is the fire of the mind,
your thoughts... Ok?!

01:49.667 --> 01:52.261
Second kind of fire is the
fire of the heart.

01:52.542 --> 01:55.091
It's your passion...

01:56.208 --> 01:58.802
and I am waiting for the third kind...

01:58.958 --> 02:02.292
and he says, then the third
kind of fire, it's just fire!

02:14.667 --> 02:18.968
They'd offered me earplugs.
Before they'd said, you will need these!

02:19.125 --> 02:21.041
And I am ah...

02:21.042 --> 02:24.342
So I used the earplugs,
it was still too loud...

02:24.500 --> 02:25.843
my body was shaking!

02:34.958 --> 02:39.509
When the fans are there it's your job
to give them bang for the buck.

02:39.667 --> 02:43.467
We are brothers in pyro! We
lead by fire.

02:49.750 --> 02:52.799
The first time I met Till,
he came into my dressing room on fire.

02:54.000 --> 02:55.092
That's a great entrance!

02:55.250 --> 02:57.673
We couldn't even shake hands,
because Till was on fire.

03:03.792 --> 03:07.001
I probably could have roasted
marshmallows from the seat I was in.

03:07.002 --> 03:08.377
And I wasn't in the front row.

03:08.542 --> 03:11.091
The production was over the
top! It was great!

03:20.708 --> 03:23.177
It's everything that Americans
think of Germany.

03:23.333 --> 03:25.631
It just runs, Germany,
it runs really well,

03:25.792 --> 03:27.715
like it's a very well oiled machine.

03:39.875 --> 03:46.167
It was an incredible display
of power and beauty,

03:46.375 --> 03:50.050
light and shade, entertainment.

03:50.208 --> 03:52.882
It was a rock opera!

03:58.792 --> 04:01.090
Their backstory is
unbelievably interesting!

04:01.250 --> 04:03.252
Six guys from behind the Iron Curtain

04:03.417 --> 04:06.045
who really did not believe they're ever
gonna have the opportunity

04:06.046 --> 04:08.340
to play the kind of music
that they are now playing.

04:09.500 --> 04:13.050
It'; The 1980s!
The East German music scene is small

04:13.208 --> 04:15.552
but active, and very tightly knit.

04:15.708 --> 04:18.382
Bands come and go,
everyone knows everyone else

04:18.541 --> 04:20.839
and there is a great sense of solidarity.

04:21.041 --> 04:23.261
On the road
with their former band 'Feeling B, '

04:23.417 --> 04:26.751
Paul Landers and Flake Lorenz
play every venue they're allowed to.

04:46.375 --> 04:50.130
Back then, it was normal
to play together with a lot of friends.

04:50.292 --> 04:53.296
If you had time,
you'd meet up and play together.

04:53.458 --> 04:55.711
'Feeling B' and 'Die
Firma' were still around

04:55.875 --> 04:57.798
so everyone had their own bands.

04:58.958 --> 05:02.542
Back then life for Paul and Flake
revolves around 'Feeling B.'

05:02.792 --> 05:06.046
Later they are joined
by drummer Christoph Schneider.

05:07.333 --> 05:11.167
In Schwerin Till Lindemann is playing
drums in the band 'First Arsch, '

05:11.333 --> 05:15.634
Richard Kruspe is with 'Das Elegante Chaos,
' and later 'Orgasm Death Gimmick, '

05:15.792 --> 05:18.796
while Oliver Riedel
is with 'The Inchtabokatables.'

05:18.958 --> 05:21.757
Their role models however
are predominantly Western.

05:22.083 --> 05:27.544
Because we could listen to radio, we had
the same radio broadcasts as West Germans.

05:27.708 --> 05:30.382
Radio Free Berlin had such great programs,

05:30.542 --> 05:34.172
and so musically we were
on the same level as the West,

05:34.375 --> 05:36.844
because music quickly crosses borders.

05:37.000 --> 05:40.800
And we knew the American bands, too.

05:51.625 --> 05:54.629
School, of course,
gave us a politically tinted view.

05:55.125 --> 05:59.426
The GDR tried to portray
the Soviet Union as good,

05:59.583 --> 06:02.553
and the West as bad, including America.

06:02.708 --> 06:04.676
It actually accomplished the opposite!

06:04.833 --> 06:11.375
I had a huge 'Kiss' poster
on my door at home,

06:11.542 --> 06:17.046
and one day my step-father came in and
ripped the poster into a thousand pieces.

06:17.047 --> 06:20.672
I spent the whole night
putting the pieces back together,

06:20.833 --> 06:23.302
and the next morning at about 5:30,
I was finished

06:23.458 --> 06:25.677
and could hang the poster back on my door.

06:25.833 --> 06:28.586
When they would be able to get their hands
on a tape, you know

06:28.750 --> 06:31.469
of a band, it was so...
It meant so much to them.

06:31.625 --> 06:37.052
So when the wall came down, obviously,
that enabled 'Rammstein' to even exist.

06:38.292 --> 06:44.046
In 1993, Schwerin friends Till, Richard and
Oliver celebrate their new found travel freedom

06:44.047 --> 06:47.046
with a voyage of discovery
across the south-western USA.

06:47.250 --> 06:51.130
Simultaneously 'Feeling B' are
visiting the south-eastern part of America.

06:51.958 --> 06:53.960
Blissfully unaware of
each other's existence,

06:54.125 --> 06:57.584
the future 'Rammstein' members
discover the formerly-forbidden country.

06:59.750 --> 07:03.675
We only knew America through films
and thought it was a dangerous country.

07:03.833 --> 07:09.636
We could speak school English,
but it wasn't enough for communication.

07:09.792 --> 07:12.511
The only one who could speak
a bit of English was Till.

07:12.667 --> 07:15.796
Oh could say “yes" and I could say "no,"
so we were a good team.

07:15.958 --> 07:20.134
Yeah, and it was terrible on the phone
when they towed our car.

07:20.292 --> 07:22.340
They were so inconsiderate,

07:22.500 --> 07:26.004
wouldn't speak a little slower,
it didn't work...

07:26.167 --> 07:29.717
We've taken your car away...
I didn't understand a word!

07:29.875 --> 07:32.958
Then they mentioned some kind of "fine,"
and I said: Is it fine?

07:33.125 --> 07:34.968
But they wanted money!

07:37.958 --> 07:40.177
Till, Oliver and Richard's traveling party

07:40.333 --> 07:43.047
don't allow themselves
to be waylaid by such problems

07:43.048 --> 07:44.885
and continue to enjoy the new world.

07:46.958 --> 07:50.132
Paul, Schneider and Flake however
take it a step further,

07:50.417 --> 07:55.674
and try to top up their depleted vacation
fund with occasional performances.

07:57.542 --> 08:01.592
When we were in New Orleans it was
Mardi Gras, which is carnival for us.

08:01.750 --> 08:07.462
There were bands playing in every bar,
there was areal party atmosphere.

08:07.750 --> 08:11.550
Then we said we'd may, too,
and suddenly the whole venue was empty!

08:11.708 --> 08:13.836
No one came in, everyone just ran out.

08:14.000 --> 08:18.301
I remember how Schneider
asked the drummer, can I play on your kit?

08:18.458 --> 08:21.382
Then the drummer looked
at Schneider's sticks,

08:21.542 --> 08:23.636
they were quite thick,

08:23.792 --> 08:27.001
and gave him two thin ones, right?

08:27.167 --> 08:28.714
He was completely over the moon.

08:28.875 --> 08:32.083
Then he gave me his sticks and I had
to keep playing with the thin ones.

08:32.250 --> 08:34.092
And he asked me not to play too hard.

08:39.292 --> 08:41.794
This American adventure
is more than just a journey

08:41.957 --> 08:44.381
through the land of
seemingly unlimited possibilities.

08:45.000 --> 08:46.843
It is also a turning point.

08:49.792 --> 08:53.717
At that time,
we were a little bit directionless.

08:53.875 --> 08:56.594
We still had the bands
that we had in the East,

08:56.750 --> 08:59.674
but we knew that we might want
to start something new.

08:59.833 --> 09:01.835
It was a kind of crossroad.

09:02.000 --> 09:05.630
For all of us, independently of each other
and both groups,

09:05.792 --> 09:10.969
seeing how music was made here, was
an inspiration that we took back to Europe.

09:11.125 --> 09:13.423
We saw that in California,

09:13.583 --> 09:17.338
there were two people in L.A.,
on Sunset Strip,

09:17.500 --> 09:19.673
listening to this band playing.

09:19.833 --> 09:23.417
They were kind of awesome in a way,
it sounded good,

09:23.583 --> 09:26.302
at least to our East German ears.

09:26.458 --> 09:31.041
There were two people in the pit,

09:31.042 --> 09:37.129
and then the band started, and they acted like
they were playing for ten thousand people.

09:37.292 --> 09:40.626
They went crazy!
I said, what'; Wrong with them?

09:40.792 --> 09:42.465
You can't go on stage like that!

09:42.625 --> 09:44.609
Because we always thought,
at the youth club,

09:44.635 --> 09:46.575
when a band plays there,
it's always packed,

09:46.708 --> 09:48.710
or there are at least a few people there.

09:48.958 --> 09:51.757
Two people! I didn't understand
why they would even start?!

09:51.917 --> 09:54.044
I thought that this is the American way,

09:54.045 --> 09:56.795
to always give one hundred percent
no matter what.

09:56.958 --> 09:59.632
I noticed that music
is more important to people here,

09:59.833 --> 10:01.756
because they have to live from it.

10:02.000 --> 10:04.594
We're from the GDR and
it was like paradise,

10:04.750 --> 10:08.002
you lived your life
and then played music on the side for fun,

10:08.003 --> 10:09.798
because there was always money.

10:10.000 --> 10:14.927
Here, people who make music are dependent
on it and therefore take it more seriously.

10:16.083 --> 10:20.008
Lives led in East Germany
and experiences gained in America...

10:20.750 --> 10:23.344
These are the foundations
on which 'Rammstein is built.

10:23.958 --> 10:25.676
The musicians also view their new band

10:25.875 --> 10:28.719
as a reaction to the situation
in the reunified Germany.

10:31.125 --> 10:35.756
We didn't want 'Rammstein'
to sound like American bands!

10:35.917 --> 10:39.922
But we adopted the energy
of the approach for our band.

10:57.042 --> 11:00.342
We conceptualized the
band to stir things up!

11:00.500 --> 11:03.094
We'd done it already
with our bands in the East,

11:03.250 --> 11:06.220
and 'Rammstein' happens
to be just what the West needs.

11:21.083 --> 11:24.667
We were never allowed to say anything,
that's how it was in the East.

11:24.833 --> 11:28.508
The problem was always
that certain topics couldn't be addressed.

11:28.667 --> 11:32.717
In music, for example,
the lyrics would be vague or in English

11:32.875 --> 11:34.798
so that no one could understand them.

11:34.958 --> 11:39.668
Then all of a sudden you have the opportunity
to say and sing whatever you want.

11:39.833 --> 11:42.256
Even do some of the things
you want to on stage,

11:42.417 --> 11:45.170
and of course in that moment
you scream it from your soul.

11:56.750 --> 12:01.130
Basically, we do what many people
would like to do.

12:02.000 --> 12:05.959
And you get the angriest about
the mistakes you'd like to make yourself.

12:06.500 --> 12:11.961
Basically, we rustle all the
feathers we can here in Germany,

12:12.250 --> 12:16.505
and people get angry
because they don't dare do it themselves.

12:27.500 --> 12:30.094
I think it's good that
'Rammstein' polarises.

12:30.095 --> 12:37.592
I like it when a band
provokes people into discussing the topic.

12:37.750 --> 12:39.468
I think it's good in general.

12:39.625 --> 12:44.051
People thinking about certain things and
then maybe even realizing where they stand,

12:44.208 --> 12:46.210
and what their own opinion is.

12:53.417 --> 12:56.138
We started as a completely normal band.
We just played.

12:56.164 --> 12:57.572
There were no show elements.

13:02.708 --> 13:05.461
Till actually saw us in Berlin 1994.

13:05.625 --> 13:08.424
He said, he was at that show
and for him and his friends,

13:08.583 --> 13:11.553
it was like one of the most
important shows they ever went to,

13:11.708 --> 13:13.301
and he said especially 'Anthrax, '

13:13.458 --> 13:17.543
because he had never seen a band
moving so much and trying to entertain

13:17.708 --> 13:20.336
and he said, it was
really, really inﬂuential on them,

13:20.500 --> 13:23.003
when they were first
putting 'Rammstein' together,

13:23.167 --> 13:25.420
thinking we want to entertain people.

13:25.583 --> 13:28.757
American audiences,
Western audiences like to be entertained!

13:28.917 --> 13:32.547
There is a long history
of entertainment from the West,

13:32.750 --> 13:35.253
starting from Elvis Presley and...

13:35.417 --> 13:40.753
but it has to have, for longevity,
it has to have some substance behind it.

13:40.917 --> 13:43.511
I know that 'Kiss, ' I am sure
was a big influence on them

13:43.667 --> 13:44.759
as they were with me.

13:44.917 --> 13:46.510
They were my heroes.

13:46.667 --> 13:51.503
The first band that introduced
certain special effects into their shows

13:51.667 --> 13:54.750
like pyrotechnics etc.,
I'd never seen that before.

13:57.583 --> 14:00.052
'Rammstein's stage show
is constantly evolving.

14:00.708 --> 14:04.667
Pyrotechnics quickly become an
integral part of their performances.

14:06.792 --> 14:09.636
Before long the band
is reaching an ever-greater audience.

14:11.042 --> 14:14.296
'Rammstein' now play major festivals
with international line-ups,

14:14.625 --> 14:17.469
and many American acts
become aware of the German band.

14:28.667 --> 14:34.549
I remember being
somewhere in Europe and hearing

14:35.875 --> 14:43.418
bubbling commentary about a new
important German group called 'Rammstein.'

14:44.333 --> 14:48.338
And it rang a strange bell,
what is 'Rammstein', 'Rammstein?'?

14:48.500 --> 14:54.257
"Stein" of course is German for "stone"
and "ramm," to "ram" is a verb in English,

14:54.417 --> 14:58.752
it'; An aggressive verb.
It means to push through

14:58.917 --> 15:00.760
and with aggressive force

15:00.917 --> 15:05.093
but I'd heard something else
and all of a sudden, I realized...

15:06.667 --> 15:10.999
Ramstein is the big American base

15:11.000 --> 15:17.963
and I thought, oh! Somebody put
their finger on the belly button.

15:23.458 --> 15:26.587
I remember,
we saw them in 1997 on this festival,

15:26.750 --> 15:30.002
And he was shooting
that ﬂamethrower out over the crowd

15:30.003 --> 15:32.628
and I remember going:
You can't do this at home!!

15:36.292 --> 15:43.710
We played at festivals in Germany
where international bands played, too.

15:43.875 --> 15:48.335
After the concert, they'd come
to us and say: You have to come over!

15:48.500 --> 15:50.218
And we always thought, what? Really?

15:50.375 --> 15:52.377
We sing in German,
no one is interested in that!

15:54.458 --> 15:56.005
Feedback from international artists,

15:56.167 --> 15:58.340
and their rising
popularity in Germany and beyond,

15:58.542 --> 16:01.233
spur 'Rammstein' on to
take the next step.

16:01.259 --> 16:04.074
The band wants to crack
the American market.

16:23.208 --> 16:26.132
The path from Germany
to America just doesn't exist.

16:26.292 --> 16:29.136
There's only the path
from America and England to Germany.

16:29.333 --> 16:31.131
There aren't even telephone lines.

16:31.292 --> 16:33.044
They don't even have the numbers!

16:33.208 --> 16:36.257
They just get called up
and told what to release.

16:37.042 --> 16:40.672
In their search for a suitable American
partner they come across Bob Biggs,

16:40.833 --> 16:43.461
founder of the
independent label 'Slash Records.'

16:43.958 --> 16:45.551
He has experience
of working with acts

16:45.708 --> 16:48.382
like 'Faith No More'
and 'Asian Dub Foundation.'

16:48.792 --> 16:51.636
Biggs decides to take a gamble
on 'Rammstein, ' and says yes.

16:52.875 --> 16:56.254
I came from a punk rock
background, I think.

16:56.417 --> 17:01.799
And I mean, the stuff that the bands
that I had were doing, was, you know...

17:01.958 --> 17:06.338
it wasn't as slick
and as produced and as good.

17:06.541 --> 17:08.795
But they were doing crazy things on stage.

17:09.000 --> 17:12.003
To understand 'Rammstein, '
you have to see 'Rammstein' live.

17:12.005 --> 17:14.878
That's why we invited him back then,

17:15.041 --> 17:17.840
and he came to see us
play at the 'Bizarre Festival'...

17:18.416 --> 17:21.090
At the time,
I had pretty much complete autonomy!

17:21.250 --> 17:23.377
I could do whatever I wanted to do,

17:24.916 --> 17:28.626
and when I first started
talking about 'Rammstein, '

17:28.792 --> 17:31.966
it wasn't really popular
within the company.

17:33.917 --> 17:38.718
Biggs is particularly fascinated by their
stage production as a total work of art.

17:41.042 --> 17:44.467
He saw it and then fell
in love with the band,

17:44.625 --> 17:50.132
and, of course, with his motivation
he accomplished a lot of things we needed.

17:50.333 --> 17:53.758
In this country, you need someone
who believes in you.

17:53.917 --> 17:58.082
And then, we brought them over to New York

17:58.083 --> 18:01.166
to play a couple of gigs,
just to get them introduced.

18:06.292 --> 18:09.298
In September 1997 the
time has finally come!

18:09.324 --> 18:11.995
'Rammstein's American
adventure begins.

18:21.292 --> 18:26.048
European success counts for little here.
America is a totally different market,

18:26.208 --> 18:29.257
in which it is difficult
for European bands to get a foothold.

18:29.542 --> 18:34.423
So, in New York,
'Rammstein' start again from scratch.

18:40.083 --> 18:43.667
This is the location
where we played for the first time.

18:43.875 --> 18:47.505
The venue was called 'Banks'
because it used to be an old bank.

18:47.667 --> 18:52.844
I recall that we played
here for about 15 people.

18:53.000 --> 18:57.301
We were playing this festival
called the 'College Music Festival.'

18:57.458 --> 19:02.168
And then, we heard a band called 'Rammstein'
was going to play the same night

19:02.333 --> 19:06.213
and we were very excited going,
who is this band from Germany?

19:06.417 --> 19:09.796
Wait a minute!
We sing in German, they sing in German.

19:09.958 --> 19:12.632
This is awesome.
We have to hang out with them, right?

19:12.792 --> 19:17.047
We sat on our gear
in the hallway when 'Rammstein' arrived.

19:17.208 --> 19:20.462
And all of them appeared
at that time to be about eight feet tall.

19:20.625 --> 19:26.553
And they just filed in one by one
in front of us, walking stoically.

19:26.708 --> 19:28.676
They came in with a smoke machine.

19:28.833 --> 19:32.042
It was like the sun was
behind them, they came in like shadows!

19:32.208 --> 19:35.004
The smoke machine
and we sat there and went like...

19:35.005 --> 19:38.550
I remember, back then,
we always started with the burning jacket.

19:38.708 --> 19:41.507
I remember that Till
set himself on fire out here,

19:41.708 --> 19:44.678
and then walked
through the venue to get to the stage.

19:44.833 --> 19:48.042
Because we didn't have a backstage
area to prepare the pyrotechnics.

19:48.208 --> 19:50.631
'Rammstein' went on considerably late

19:50.833 --> 19:54.292
and played to
about 30 people, two of which were us.

19:54.458 --> 19:59.840
Of course, we waited around
and we were just, it was just like...

20:00.000 --> 20:04.836
It was insane, it was
an arena show in a bar, it was a barena!

20:35.875 --> 20:38.958
Bob had said to me,
you need to go check out this band!

20:39.125 --> 20:41.378
They are gonna be
a very big priority for you!

20:41.542 --> 20:44.967
You're gonna have to work this and
we're putting this album out in January!

20:45.958 --> 20:49.542
And I remember watching
this and seeing this

20:49.750 --> 20:53.505
and saying to myself:
This is it? This is the big priority?

20:55.875 --> 20:58.594
The German band's
show causes jaws to drop.

20:59.375 --> 21:02.709
The press now take notice of the six
lads from the fallen East Germany,

21:03.042 --> 21:06.012
not least of all due to
the band's extreme physical exertion.

21:07.542 --> 21:11.217
Back then,
we had a song that we played called...

21:12.792 --> 21:13.964
what was it called again?

21:14.125 --> 21:15.468
“Ich tu dir weh."
“Feuerréider."

21:15.625 --> 21:17.548
No, "Feuerrader!"
Yeah! That's what I meant.

21:18.417 --> 21:23.503
That was the performance
where Flake rode around on Till for a while

21:23.708 --> 21:26.302
with a neon tube
in his hand, and then, for the finale,

21:26.458 --> 21:30.838
would basically shatter it
into a thousand pieces on Till's back.

21:31.000 --> 21:36.082
German neon tubes are thin
and very easy to break.

21:36.083 --> 21:41.510
But Flake didn't know that American neon
tubes are about three to four times thicker

21:41.667 --> 21:43.385
and not as easily shattered.

21:43.542 --> 21:48.082
Exactly! So he went nuts
trying to break it on Till's back.

21:48.083 --> 21:51.004
Poor Till almost couldn't
handle it anymore,

21:51.005 --> 21:55.801
and at the end it didn't really shatter,
it just broke into two pieces.

21:55.958 --> 22:02.671
The other piece ﬂew at me while I was playing
and suddenly it was stuck in my shoulder!

22:02.833 --> 22:05.552
And then we all went out onto the street

22:05.708 --> 22:09.417
where Till and I bled like crazy.

22:09.583 --> 22:13.417
Till'; Back looked really bad!
It was full of shards.

22:13.583 --> 22:15.301
That was our first show in America.

22:15.458 --> 22:18.667
It was like trial by fire!
We're seeing it live in a small club

22:18.833 --> 22:22.463
with them playing and smashing
ﬂuorescent lights across each other.

22:22.667 --> 22:26.092
I left and I just remember
walking out shaking my head and saying:

22:26.250 --> 22:30.175
What am I gonna do with these guys?
How is this gonna work?

22:30.375 --> 22:33.504
Listen to the band! It
didn't really matter!

22:33.667 --> 22:39.424
I mean the trilling of
the German like an opera singer,

22:39.667 --> 22:44.252
and the way it came out and the attack that
it had and the point that the music had,

22:44.417 --> 22:48.797
was so aggressive and so, so, so striking!

22:48.958 --> 22:51.047
I didn't really care what was going on.

22:51.048 --> 22:54.251
It didn't matter to me,
I just thought it was wonderful stuff.

22:59.583 --> 23:02.587
A mere three months
later, in December 1997,

23:02.750 --> 23:08.712
'Rammstein' embark upon their first major U.S.
tour, supporting the industrial band 'KMFDM.'

23:31.583 --> 23:34.462
Pyrotechnics are
'Rammstein's trump card at this point.

23:35.542 --> 23:38.842
I ﬂew out to come and see the band,
to see them perform,

23:39.000 --> 23:41.844
to see them really let loose.

23:42.000 --> 23:44.002
I'll never forget, the show ended.

23:44.003 --> 23:49.211
The end of the show, Till held out the
ﬂamethrower and was blowing ﬂames,

23:49.375 --> 23:53.960
it couldn't have been more than 25
or 30 feet over the crowds head

23:54.125 --> 23:56.719
and I saw the reaction of the crowd.

23:56.875 --> 24:01.255
And I remember leaving that show
that night and realizing this could work!

24:01.417 --> 24:05.297
So that was the next step
for me to sort of believing

24:05.500 --> 24:08.299
and seeing what 'Rammstein'
could really ultimately achieve.

24:11.042 --> 24:14.967
The band still lack an American agent
who can book shows for them in the U.S.

24:15.875 --> 24:19.550
As a result Wayne Pighini
has to do an awful lot of persuading.

24:22.292 --> 24:26.001
He had called me and said, we are
looking for an agent for this band

24:26.002 --> 24:28.001
and I think you would be perfect.

24:28.002 --> 24:29.547
Your company represents 'Metallica, '

24:29.708 --> 24:31.836
you've some
of the biggest artists in the world,

24:32.000 --> 24:37.586
but my initial instinct was,
that this will never, ever work in America.

24:37.750 --> 24:41.254
So I called Wayne
and I said, I'm passing, I'm out,

24:41.417 --> 24:43.260
it's never gonna happen here!

24:43.417 --> 24:46.626
Americans will never listen
to a band that sings in German.

24:47.333 --> 24:50.416
And he wouldn't give up! So I said, OK!

24:50.583 --> 24:52.585
Listen! I'm gonna go see the show.

24:53.292 --> 24:58.041
So I went to Los Angeles,
I walked into the Palladium,

24:58.042 --> 24:59.009
'Rammstein' comes out,

25:02.375 --> 25:06.926
Till has his arms open with the
metal jacket, completely on fire...

25:10.167 --> 25:12.420
I looked at Wayne and I said, I'm in!

25:12.958 --> 25:18.169
This is so extreme, this is so real,
that America will eat this up!

25:18.792 --> 25:24.046
The biggest dream for every band from Europe
or Germany is to be successful in America.

25:24.047 --> 25:28.673
If you're then lucky enough
to gain that success in your own language

25:28.833 --> 25:30.676
without having to imitate anything,

25:30.833 --> 25:34.258
if you can stay true
to yourself, your music and language,

25:34.417 --> 25:36.294
you feel even better, of course.

25:42.958 --> 25:46.417
That'; Why these concerts
were incredibly important to us.

25:46.583 --> 25:51.544
That we managed, after a certain time, after
we'd already been successful in Germany,

25:51.708 --> 25:55.042
to do concerts here with 'Rammstein.'

25:55.208 --> 25:59.839
Because we just knew that our show,
the pyrotechnics and everything,

26:00.000 --> 26:04.085
would also be well received in America,
regardless of whether we sang in German,

26:04.250 --> 26:07.959
we knew that it was definitely worth
trying to come here with 'Rammstein.'

26:12.000 --> 26:15.459
So it's possible that someone would go
to a 'Rammstein' show in the States

26:15.625 --> 26:18.549
and have no interest
in guitar-based music or heavy metal,

26:18.708 --> 26:21.336
but they just love
the fireworks and the spectacle.

26:21.500 --> 26:26.085
The first headline tour that
we booked for 'Rammstein' across the U.S.,

26:26.250 --> 26:31.461
we did San Francisco,
L.A., Denver, Chicago and New York.

26:31.625 --> 26:33.999
It's 1,200 miles to Denver!

26:34.000 --> 26:34.751
From where?

26:34.917 --> 26:36.919
From L.A.

26:39.000 --> 26:41.094
Maybe we should leave earlier.

26:44.667 --> 26:52.667
Presale! Denver 464!
Chicago 740! Presale! 740!

26:52.875 --> 26:56.334
Fucking beautiful!
520 New York City!

26:56.500 --> 27:02.633
Two weeks left! Looking good! Very good.

27:05.000 --> 27:06.502
Kids were coming to the show,

27:06.667 --> 27:10.376
knowing that they were gonna see an
incredible, intense show with pyrotechnics!

27:10.542 --> 27:13.751
And the band
was challenged every day by the authorities

27:13.917 --> 27:16.090
as to what they could do or couldn't do.

27:31.292 --> 27:35.342
<i>When we were</i> in <i>Chicago in 1998,
the fire department</i> came <i>down to the</i> show

27:35.500 --> 27:38.299
and they told them
they were not allowed to do fire!

27:38.500 --> 27:43.256
And they were like: Oh, my God!
How we gonna do a show, without FEUER?!

27:50.583 --> 27:54.042
So the band had two choices! One: Go home!

27:54.208 --> 27:56.461
Two: Do a show with no pyro!

27:58.250 --> 28:00.719
So they said: Fuck it!
There's 1,100 people here,

28:00.875 --> 28:03.424
we're gonna play without pyro
and we're gonna kick some ass!

28:04.875 --> 28:07.048
We didn't know that almost every type

28:07.208 --> 28:10.417
of pyrotechnics needed
to be inspected for permission!

28:18.375 --> 28:25.714
One of the drawbacks is that everyone here
in America takes their job so seriously!

28:25.875 --> 28:29.800
150 percent seriously,
and you have to show them everything.

28:29.958 --> 28:32.381
Even to this day, the band will not play,

28:32.542 --> 28:35.087
cannot play in the city limits of Chicago,

28:35.088 --> 28:38.713
because they had massive fires
way back in the early 1900s.

28:44.708 --> 28:48.838
But the band receive surprising support
of a very different kind from Hollywood.

28:49.458 --> 28:53.041
Visionary director David Lynch
uses two of their songs

28:53.042 --> 28:55.340
in his now-legendary film 'Lost Highway.'

29:21.708 --> 29:25.292
Lynch was definitely a door-opener.

29:25.458 --> 29:29.543
A door opened for us
into that style of art.

29:29.750 --> 29:33.550
All these intellectuals,
noticed us for the first time.

29:33.708 --> 29:36.552
I mean, Manson was involved.

29:36.708 --> 29:39.962
Trent Reznor of 'Nine Inch Nails'
did the soundtrack back then,

29:40.125 --> 29:42.548
so it was a good soundtrack
with Lynch, yeah.

29:54.708 --> 29:57.052
I was playing a prisoner in the jail scene.

29:57.208 --> 29:59.427
Henry Rollins was the prison guard.

29:59.583 --> 30:05.005
So during that scene on the set David Lynch
was playing this music to set the mood.

30:05.006 --> 30:08.254
Because he wanted it to be
very dark and very scary.

30:08.417 --> 30:11.041
Start the music quiet!

30:11.042 --> 30:15.343
And then, when it hits the quiet part of the
music, we'll crank it up on action, OK?!

30:17.000 --> 30:20.550
So he starts playing
this song: "Rammstein!“"

30:33.042 --> 30:34.510
I never heard it before!

30:34.667 --> 30:38.592
He's playing this really evil heavy music
with some guy with this voice

30:38.750 --> 30:42.050
and singing in German!
And I am like, this is fucked up!

30:42.208 --> 30:45.758
I'm sitting in this weird jail cell
and I've never been in a movie before,

30:45.917 --> 30:49.342
so I was nervous anyway
and the music just made me more nervous

30:49.500 --> 30:52.089
and that was the point.
David Lynch was like:

30:52.090 --> 30:55.337
I want everyone to look really nervous
and scared, and the music did it!

30:55.500 --> 30:58.674
And then I asked afterwards.
I said, what'; That music you're playing?

30:58.833 --> 31:02.588
He goes: They're this German band
called 'Rammstein!' Isn't it great?!

31:04.208 --> 31:08.384
I mean certainly
having 'Rammstein' in 'Lost Highway'

31:08.542 --> 31:12.718
was the introduction
that 'Rammstein' had to a lot of Americans.

31:12.917 --> 31:16.592
I think, they still
would have had success without that,

31:16.750 --> 31:22.553
but it's such an amazing scene
and the music works so perfectly.

31:39.125 --> 31:42.629
You know, it's hard to imagine
that scene with any other music in there.

32:04.042 --> 32:07.467
I was involved with
David Lynch making 'Lost Highway'

32:08.208 --> 32:13.009
and I had heard some music
that he was considering using for the film

32:13.167 --> 32:16.751
and for some reason, he had asked me
about 'Rammstein'.

32:16.917 --> 32:22.999
And it ended up being in the sex scene
when fucking somebody: Patricia Arquette.

32:23.000 --> 32:25.001
So that's where it first started with,

32:25.002 --> 32:28.709
so I hopefully had a part
of the suggestion to David Lynch

32:28.875 --> 32:30.969
because I was such a fan of the song.

32:51.583 --> 32:55.668
At that point, David Lynch
and Trent Reznor were like demigods.

32:55.833 --> 32:58.837
And so David Lynch and Trent Reznor
saying that they liked 'Rammstein'

32:59.000 --> 33:01.970
suddenly made it OK for everyone else
in America to like 'Rammstein.'

33:02.125 --> 33:05.504
Cut it! Good deal!

33:07.667 --> 33:08.668
We're there, man!

33:08.833 --> 33:14.135
I think we gained
a lot of hardcore fans at that time.

33:14.292 --> 33:19.719
People that listened to that type of music,
not the mainstream public.

33:19.875 --> 33:25.041
But these were the first fans
to notice 'Rammstein' in America.

33:25.042 --> 33:27.261
So, the first American
interview they did here

33:27.417 --> 33:29.966
was with a major
fashion magazine, was with 'Details?

33:30.125 --> 33:32.048
And I knew it was the right thing to do,

33:32.208 --> 33:36.041
as soon as people started calling up
and saying: How the fuck did that happen?

33:36.042 --> 33:40.172
I was just working on these things, like
I wanted them to be in 'Details' or 'GQ'

33:40.333 --> 33:43.052
or 'Esquire' or 'Vanity Fair'
first before anything else

33:43.053 --> 33:45.591
and 'MTV' started getting into them,

33:45.750 --> 33:49.584
ready to do some sort of
Headbangers' Ball rock thing

33:49.750 --> 33:53.129
and I said, no, I didn't wanna do it
until Kurt Loder did it himself

33:53.292 --> 33:55.670
and I also knew that
Kurt Loder spoke German.

33:56.458 --> 33:59.462
Metal isn't a musical combination
one comes across every day.

33:59.625 --> 34:02.299
When the German band 'Rammstein'
passed through New York recently,

34:02.458 --> 34:04.802
in ﬂames literally,
we had to catch their act.

34:04.958 --> 34:07.211
The group is fronted by
an Olympic swimming champ,

34:07.375 --> 34:09.045
oddly enough has already been featured

34:09.045 --> 34:11.170
on a soundtrack
of David Lynch's film 'Lost Highway'

34:11.333 --> 34:12.380
and doesn't speak English.

34:12.542 --> 34:16.172
So in a tribute to Raymond Burr's placed-in
appearance in the original 'Godzilla'

34:16.333 --> 34:19.757
we dusted off our rusty German and
pretaped some questions to put to the boys.

34:19.917 --> 34:21.965
It seemed like a good idea, but let's see.

34:22.125 --> 34:25.254
Good evening, gentlemen.
So tell me what's going on with the fire?

34:25.417 --> 34:28.545
There's fire in the videos and fire
on stage, what's up with that?

34:28.708 --> 34:32.007
It's important to have
something more than just for your ears,

34:32.167 --> 34:34.795
because that's what you
get on the CD at home.

34:34.958 --> 34:39.134
It was always my experience
that when I went to a concert,

34:39.292 --> 34:42.670
I wanted to see something other
than the music.

34:42.833 --> 34:44.050
Isn't that dangerous?

34:44.208 --> 34:50.375
Only minor things have happened to us,
like light to moderate burns sometimes,

34:50.542 --> 34:53.625
some singed hair
and maybe a burnt ear and...

35:05.917 --> 35:09.044
those guys 'Rammstein.'
Please don't try this at home, kids!

35:09.045 --> 35:10.214
Guitars can be dangerous!

35:10.458 --> 35:14.543
At the time, the music scene was
the 'Spice Girls' and stuff like that.

35:14.708 --> 35:16.585
It was 'Hanson, ' it was terrible!

35:16.750 --> 35:21.677
And it was also this new metal scene with
'Korn' and 'Linkin Park' and those guys.

35:21.833 --> 35:24.131
'Korn' and 'Linkin Park' were
pretty powerful bands,

35:24.292 --> 35:27.375
but they weren't as interesting to look at
as 'Rammstein' was.

35:27.542 --> 35:32.002
They were just very theatrical sort of
like 'Kiss' in away.

35:32.167 --> 35:36.468
So they were much more interesting I thought
and they knew exactly what they were doing.

35:36.625 --> 35:40.129
Till is a great singer.
And I just loved it,

35:40.292 --> 35:43.546
"I love “Du Hast" and I love that album,
it's really great.

35:53.167 --> 35:56.250
Hard heavy music, metal,
whatever you want to call it,

35:56.417 --> 35:58.465
was really on an upswing at that time

35:58.625 --> 36:02.835
in the form of bands like 'Limp Bizkit,
' 'Korn, ' 'System of a Down, '

36:03.000 --> 36:04.968
'Tool, ' 'Rage Against the Machine, '

36:05.125 --> 36:09.756
these bands at that time were starting
to become really popular mainstream

36:09.917 --> 36:12.261
and radio had to support that.

36:12.417 --> 36:16.001
Again these bands
were just getting too big outside of radio

36:16.167 --> 36:21.469
and that whole movement
of heavy bands really sort of had dictated

36:21.625 --> 36:24.344
a new direction for radio stations.

36:30.917 --> 36:37.209
Alternative radio in the States was
'jewel' and 'The Wallﬂowers'

36:37.375 --> 36:40.629
and was very lighthearted.

36:40.792 --> 36:44.751
And then almost over night,
it became 'Metallica, ' 'Limp Bizkit, '

36:44.917 --> 36:48.842
'Puddle of Mudd, ' 'Disturbed'
and 'Rammstein' fit perfectly into that.

36:56.625 --> 37:00.459
The only other German band
we really knew was 'The Scorpions' before.

37:00.625 --> 37:03.003
And, you know, they always sang in English.

37:03.004 --> 37:08.382
So it was very interesting to see
this band playing such heavy, heavy music

37:08.542 --> 37:09.964
and singing in German,

37:10.125 --> 37:13.049
and American kids loving it, they loved it.

37:13.250 --> 37:17.505
Because think about it,
before that it was "99 Luftballons.“".

37:17.667 --> 37:21.797
So you got, it was 'Nena, ' 'Rammstein.'

37:37.208 --> 37:43.750
it seems like every decade, there is one
German song that is incredibly pervasive.

37:43.958 --> 37:49.510
And it seems like this country allows only
one German song per decade to be a hit.

37:49.667 --> 37:53.752
'Rammstein' were fortunate enough
to get the 90s.

37:57.167 --> 38:00.501
'Rammstein's single “Du Hast"
becomes that hit song.

38:00.958 --> 38:03.256
Even the smallest radio stations play it.

38:03.875 --> 38:08.210
'Rammstein' have managed something that has
eluded almost all other German artists -

38:08.625 --> 38:10.047
they've broken America.

38:10.625 --> 38:14.082
I'm from a very small town
in the United States.

38:14.083 --> 38:17.166
It's very unexpected that
they would even play the song.

38:17.333 --> 38:23.591
And I remember right away,
I loved the production, the sound

38:23.750 --> 38:27.835
and I remember I had to
ask someone right away what that meant.

38:28.000 --> 38:33.507
And I felt anytime
someone has to question art,

38:33.667 --> 38:36.637
it means something to you!

38:36.792 --> 38:38.965
It doesn't pass you right by!

38:52.583 --> 38:55.632
At the time MTV was very important.

38:55.792 --> 38:59.046
You had to be on MTV! So, 'cause
then your fans can see who you are.

38:59.208 --> 39:02.792
They wanted to crack this market obviously.
They wanted to be big in America!

39:02.958 --> 39:10.082
Be afraid, be very afraid, if you love
having the holy crap scared out of you,

39:10.083 --> 39:13.292
and I know I do, then you
are gonna love this!

39:13.458 --> 39:18.669
Performing "DU HAST",
oh my sweet lord, it's 'RAMMSTEIN!!'

39:41.125 --> 39:44.504
Once U.S. radio got a hold of it
and saw the reaction

39:44.667 --> 39:46.635
and how it worked and MTV played it,

39:46.792 --> 39:52.549
it just continued to snowball
and it was everywhere.

39:52.708 --> 39:56.383
I remember a friend of mine at MTV called
me up and said, oh hey,

39:56.542 --> 40:01.127
they passed on this third 'Smashing Pumpkins'
video of whatever the album was at that time

40:01.292 --> 40:03.135
and they're giving the spot to your hand.

40:03.292 --> 40:05.465
I was like what band? Like 'Rammstein, '

40:05.625 --> 40:07.923
they're gonna put "Du Hast"
into heavy rotation.

40:08.292 --> 40:11.136
I had just left 'Hole, ' just joined
'The Smashing Pumpkins'

40:11.292 --> 40:15.502
and I remember james Iha,
the guitar player in the Pumpkins,

40:15.667 --> 40:20.218
during like between songs just started
going "du, du hast, du hast mich"

40:20.375 --> 40:23.834
and got the whole crowd to chant
and that was my introduction,

40:24.000 --> 40:28.085
was through the guitar player of 'Smashing
Pumpkins' doing an a cappella chant.

41:57.125 --> 42:00.834
One of the greatest things I remember,
was walking into a strip club

42:01.000 --> 42:02.718
and I don't frequent strip clubs,

42:02.875 --> 42:07.551
but when I heard "Du Hast"
at the strip club, I knew the band made it.

42:08.500 --> 42:13.506
Boosted by this success, the album "Sehnsucht"
climbs into the American Billboard Top 50 -

42:13.750 --> 42:16.833
a massive success
for a German band with German lyrics.

42:17.167 --> 42:19.465
In the summer of 1998 'Rammstein, '

42:19.625 --> 42:21.969
in conjunction
with some of America's hottest bands,

42:22.125 --> 42:24.219
launch the 'Family Values Tour.'

42:24.833 --> 42:28.588
Every town we went to at first,
the people all stood like this!

42:28.750 --> 42:29.876
What is that?

42:45.500 --> 42:49.130
The 'Family Values' name was
kind of like this group of bands.

42:49.292 --> 42:52.751
Ironically 'Rammstein' was really
the black sheep in that group,

42:52.917 --> 42:57.468
they really had nothing to do with those
bands other then being classified in the.

42:57.625 --> 43:03.041
U.S. music marketing
machine as a metal band.

43:03.042 --> 43:06.251
It was always encouraging
to play with these cool bands,

43:06.417 --> 43:09.296
because we really had
the creme de la creme.

43:09.458 --> 43:15.591
They set quite a high standard
and we could only just keep up.

43:15.750 --> 43:19.505
Or let's put it this way,
it was a good measuring stick for us.

43:19.667 --> 43:23.044
Because it's easy
to be the king back home in Germany.

43:23.045 --> 43:27.252
But to keep up internationally,
that's something else entirely!

43:50.792 --> 43:55.082
They were embraced in this group,
in this tour

43:55.083 --> 44:00.795
which was built as 'Family Values' because at
the time "Du Hast“ was exploding in the U.S."

44:30.667 --> 44:34.672
I think we were supposed
to play third or second, in the lead-up.

44:35.875 --> 44:40.335
Then we told our management:
We won't play second out of five bands!

44:40.500 --> 44:43.583
We'll play second to last!
We want to play right before 'Korn!'

44:43.750 --> 44:47.050
And 'Limp Bizkit' was lethal!
So lethal live, really!

44:47.051 --> 44:48.919
They went off!

45:01.417 --> 45:06.127
We felt really shabby! We thought,
they're cool, hard, make awesome music,

45:06.292 --> 45:08.715
and we've snuck in, unjustified,

45:08.875 --> 45:11.845
and are trying to mask it
with a few ﬂamethrowers!

45:20.792 --> 45:25.423
Their music is heavy,
but it almost sounds military,

45:25.583 --> 45:33.126
almost sounds like a squadron
of military musicians has come on stage.

45:41.167 --> 45:44.671
I don't think the audience really knew
what hit them over their head.

45:44.833 --> 45:49.634
It felt like sort of this band coming on

45:49.792 --> 45:53.126
with fire and destruction and death

45:53.292 --> 45:56.067
and by the time it was over,
it was like: "What happened?

45:56.093 --> 45:57.527
What just happened to us?!“."

45:57.667 --> 46:01.217
It was complete entertainment,
the whole time from start to finish!

46:09.417 --> 46:12.131
I remember that on the
'Family Values Tour',

46:12.157 --> 46:14.448
I had a huge problem
just being there

46:14.583 --> 46:17.006
because I couldn't speak a word of English!

46:17.167 --> 46:19.465
So I closed myself off.

46:19.625 --> 46:22.094
I thought it was such a shame,
because I wanted to,

46:22.292 --> 46:24.966
I mean we were playing
with bands that we all liked.

46:25.125 --> 46:28.174
But I never had the chance to communicate!

46:28.333 --> 46:33.590
I was very introverted there, and I suffered
a lot because I couldn't speak the language.

46:34.000 --> 46:36.161
It was strange for us,
the first time them coming over,

46:36.250 --> 46:38.850
we're going to the dressing room
and they're having a table set up

46:39.000 --> 46:40.718
and they'll have a traditional dinner set,

46:40.875 --> 46:43.355
they were all sitting like
eating together at a table and like:

46:43.458 --> 46:45.418
"What the hell is going on
in this dressing room?"

46:47.500 --> 46:49.594
It was very hard to
communicate with the band.

46:49.750 --> 46:52.503
It was very difficult to try to translate

46:52.667 --> 46:57.001
and explain to them some laws and things,
really more cultural things.

46:57.002 --> 47:00.504
You know the laws are different
in every state in the United States.

47:00.667 --> 47:05.423
So the fire marshal would come in
and they would allow this in one city

47:05.583 --> 47:07.585
and not allow that in one city.

47:08.917 --> 47:11.082
I still have language problems!

47:11.083 --> 47:15.293
My English is so bad that those
who understand it turn away from me

47:15.458 --> 47:18.177
and hope that my speech is almost over,

47:18.333 --> 47:22.088
or make a face
